text:
Tips for trident hunting :

- Drowned spawn anywhere in ocean and river biomes at light levels 7 or less, so you can have drowned spawn during the day provided you dive deep enough (door trick for O2 if needed)

- River biomes have a slightly higher spawn rate, but it's a bad idea to hunt there, unless you spawn-proof the whole land around it in a 128 blocks radius to avoid land mobs

- Ocean ruins are generated originally with a few drowned, but once you've killed those, there is nothing special about the spawn rate around ocean ruins (actually they are worse unless you get rid of the light sources like sea lanterns and magma blocks)

- The best situation (setting aside trident farms) is to settle camp on a small island (or artificial platform) in the middle of a deep ocean and far away from land, and just grind there

- understand that it's a numbers' game (6.25% of drowned spawn with a trident, and after that drop rate is between 8.5% and 11.5% depending if you have looting) so you should really go after drowned and chain-kill them all, including those who don't have tridents, just to make room for new drowned to spawn. Don't just stand in place waiting, nor flee from them. This will also prevent you getting swarmed when a drowned with trident finally spawns.

- Shields are the counter to tridents, use it to go after drowned in melee

- This last point is not just for trident hunting, but a general advice for all enemy encounters : Don't spam-click your attacks like a maniac, you're actually dealing WAY less damage that way. Always let the little sword-shaped grey bar under your cross-hair fill up, as this represents the cooldown for max swing damage. Spam-clicking is why you get swarmed and mogged by mobs that should pose you no threat by now.
